Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1911, Ronald Reagan, who would later become the 40th president of the United States, was born.

Reagan was raised in poverty and graduated from college during the Great Depression. He worked in radio before transitioning to Hollywood, signing a contract with Warner Brothers. Over his film career, he starred in over 50 films.

Reagan served two terms as California's governor and then ran for president in 1976, losing to Gerald Ford. He won the Republican nomination in 1980 and defeated incumbent Jimmy Carter to become president. At 69, he was the oldest person to hold the office. Known as the "Great Communicator," Reagan inspired hope and optimism in Americans, helping to restore faith in the government and the presidency after years of disillusionment. After leaving office, Reagan revealed he had Alzheimer's disease, and he passed away in 2004 at 93.

The rising costs of healthcare are one of the most pressing issues I hear about from members of our community. Addressing this issue is a top priority for me, which is why I introduced the bipartisan HOPE Act. No family should have to choose between their health and financial security.

Here‚Äôs what the HOPE Act does:

‚úÖ Creates HOPE Accounts, a tax-free savings tool for medical expenses  
‚úÖ Puts families in control  
‚úÖ Allows contributions from employers and individuals to reduce out-of-pocket costs  
‚úÖ Ensures tax-free growth for medical expenses, helping families plan for the future  

As healthcare costs continue to outpace inflation and wage growth, the HOPE Act provides a long-overdue solution to assist families in managing out-of-pocket medical expenses.

text:
üö® BIG NEWS!! üö®

Since first being elected as Co-Chair of the Bipartisan Problem Solvers Caucus, rooted in my core belief that Bipartisanship and Two-Party solutions are the only things that will protect and preserve our democracy, I have made it my mission to enact and enforce two critical reforms to the By-Laws of the Problem Solvers Caucus: 

First, to implement bipartisan ‚Äúcourage metrics‚Äù based on actual floor votes, to ensure that bipartisanship and independent voting is a 50-50 two-way street. 

And second, to enshrine mandatory term limits for Caucus leadership, to afford everyone in the Caucus the opportunity to lead and to prevent Caucus ‚Äúdictatorships.‚Äù These two legacy-defining issues have been my #1 priority, to ensure that our 100% focus is on the good of the Caucus, the good of Bipartisanship, and the good of our Country, not the good of the individual.  

I am so please to announce that today, with the assistance and fresh new leadership of my friend @RepTomSuozzi, as well as the leadership of our friends @RepEdCase, @RepGarbarino, @RepLaLota, & @RepSusieLee, these two goals have been realized. 

Monitoring and enforcing these metrics will be an ongoing mission, but this is a pivotal and seminal moment for the @ProbSolveCaucus, the only bipartisan two-party caucus in Congress. More importantly, this is a great moment for the United States of America, and all who are believers in two-party solutions. üá∫üá∏

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
I am deeply concerned by the role Elon Musk is playing in the Trump administration. The President has given Musk broad, sweeping power with no clear definition or boundary. Musk is using that power in ways both illegal and destructive.

He has blocked payments duly approved by Congress and signed into law by the President. This is illegal. He has completely shut down U.S. foreign aid, blocking payments of programs already approved that millions of people across the world are counting on for food security and health care among other needs. Agencies providing crucial services to people in desperate circumstances are headed into bankruptcy as a result of these funds being cut off.

He is also randomly threatening or firing thousands of government employees in ways that jeopardize their ability to do their jobs and may also violate employment law. Just days before the fatal plane crash in Washington D.C., Musk‚Äôs DOGE task force offered all FAA employees eight month‚Äôs pay in exchange for quitting, leaving them to wonder if they might be fired at some point if they didn‚Äôt accept the offer. Chaos, uncertainty and threats are making it impossible for federal employees to do their jobs in far too many instances.

I strongly support the idea of making government more efficient and more effective. Meaningful reform is needed, and Mr. Musk certainly has the background and experience to help accomplish these goals. He should focus on that and stop randomly terrorizing federal employees and illegally cutting off funds duly approved by Congress and being depended on by people in desperate need of help.

With @realDonaldTrump and @DOGE achieving historic victories for the American people by slashing a bloated federal machine spewing our tax dollars in every direction‚Ä¶

It‚Äôs time to pull the REINS on regulatory overreach. 

Today, I joined @SenRandPaul to introduce the Regulations from the Executive In Need of Scrutiny (REINS) Act for the 119th Congress. 

This legislation would require that federal regulations with an economic impact of $100 million or more be subject to an up-or-down vote in Congress, reclaiming legislative power from the regulatory state.

Without the REINS Act, Americans will continue to live under the tyranny of unelected bureaucrats who effectively make laws but never have to stand for election. 

But with REINS, Congress has an opportunity to restore its constitutional lawmaking role while saving countless American workers, consumers, businesses, and families from the costs imposed by endless federal regulations.

We cannot allow future administrations to undo the great achievements and reforms of the federal government that President Trump is making today.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1984, Navy Captain Bruce McCandless II became the first person to perform an untethered spacewalk.

While orbiting 170 miles above Earth, he exited the U.S. space shuttle Challenger and freely maneuvered using a jet pack of his own design. Traveling at speeds over 17,500 miles per hour, McCandless flew up to 320 feet from the shuttle, testing the jet pack for an hour and a half before safely returning. The device was seen as a key development for future satellite repairs and space station maintenance. This was the fourth mission of the Challenger.

Name: Murphy, Christopher

text: 3/ Musk and Trump are dismantling our counter-China efforts, including USAID. It's not a coincidence that they and their billionaire friends have outsourced millions of jobs to China (Musk makes half his cars there!) and they don't want China to be mad and hurt their profits.

text: 3/ Here's what my team found out about the "waivers". First, Rubio's people aren't actually letting orgs file waivers. They are telling them to wait, wait, wait for something called "guidance". But no guidance comes so most waivers can't be filed.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 5/ Ok, so maybe get some staff to issue the guidance or turn the payment system back on. But...wait for it...THERE'S NO STAFF TO DO IT! Musk laid of 98% of USAID staff so there's no one to process the waivers.

text: 4/ Second, even if a waiver is granted, the Payment Management system is TURNED OFF! So even if a key counter-China or counter-terrorism program gets a waiver, it doesn't matter because there's no money to pay staff or run programming. See the game here?

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
I sat down with @Amtrak CEO Stephen Gardner and President Roger Harris for a critical conversation on the future of America‚Äôs rail infrastructure. Amtrak is not just a transportation provider‚Äîit‚Äôs a major carrier, employer, and economic engine for Bucks and Montgomery Counties, and a cornerstone of our national transit network.

We discussed strategies to enhance the passenger experience, improve efficiency, and strengthen rail service for communities across the country. Thanks to the bipartisan Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act‚Äîwhich I was proud to help architect‚Äîwe are making historic investments in modernizing our rail system, including the launch of the next-generation Acela this spring. But there‚Äôs more work to do.

Thank you to Stephen and Roger for your time and leadership‚ÄîI look forward to continuing working alongside you and remain committed to fighting for strong passenger rail and transit programs that ensure Amtrak has the resources it‚Äôs need to expand service, increase reliability, and keep our communities and economy moving forward.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Julius Walker, Jr., who resides in Roper, is a retired educator who enjoyed a 45-year career in Washington County. During his tenure, he held various roles, including teacher, coach, principal, assistant superintendent, and superintendent.

Julius has been a positive role model throughout his career, mentoring students and staff. In addition to his work in education, Julius remains deeply involved in his community. He serves on numerous boards and organizations, including the Washington County Board of Commissioners, where he was chair in 2017, and the Washington County Social Services Board. He also holds leadership positions on the Northeast Regional School of Biotechnical Agri-Science Board, the Washington-Tyrrell Partnership for Children, and the Juvenile Court Justice Board. His commitment extends to organizations such as the NAACP, the Beaufort Community College Board of Trustees, and Morning Star AME Zion Church, where he serves as a steward and Sunday school superintendent.

Through his decades of service, Julius Walker, Jr. has exemplified the values of education, leadership, and community commitment, leaving a lasting legacy of positive change and empowerment.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share the stories of extraordinary individuals whose leadership, service, and dedication strengthen the fabric of our community. This morning, I stood on the floor of the House to honor the life and legacy of a remarkable leader, advocate, and fighter‚Äîa true hometown hero‚Äîthe remarkable Anna Payne, Middletown Supervisor, whom we sadly lost this week.
¬†
A Levittown native and Neshaminy High School graduate, Anna was more than a public servant‚Äîshe was a champion for her neighbors, a tireless advocate for the most vulnerable, and a fearless leader who turned her battles into a mission to uplift others. She didn‚Äôt just believe in community‚Äîshe built it, strengthened it, and fought for it every day.
¬†
Diagnosed with cystic fibrosis at a young age, Anna understood struggle but refused to be defined by it. Instead, it inspired her to work tirelessly to make life better for others. Through her leadership as Vice Chair of the @PARareDisease and as the founder of the Bucks County Cystic Fibrosis Alliance, Anna gave hope to countless families and individuals in our community. As Middletown Township Supervisor, she was a fierce and effective leader, working to make our community stronger, safer, and more connected, championing initiatives that enhanced local infrastructure, protected public safety, and bettered our community.
¬†
Even after her stage-four colon cancer diagnosis in 2021, Anna never wavered in her commitment to our community. Through unimaginable adversity, she continued showing up‚Äîproving time and time again that her dedication, resilience, and heart knew no bounds. Her impact stretched far beyond the halls of government; she was a mentor, a friend, and a guiding light to all who knew her. Through her tireless healthcare advocacy, unwavering commitment to local initiatives, and extraordinary ability to unite people, Anna exemplified the best of Bucks County.
¬†
Today, we mourn the loss of a true hometown hero, but more importantly,¬† we celebrate a legacy that will never fade and honor a life of service and unyielding determination. Please join me in honoring Anna‚Äîa woman whose strength, service, and spirit will forever be woven into the fabric of our community.

Name: Bilirakis, Gus M.
text: We are committed to restoring American Energy Dominance, part of which requires unleashing all safe means of domestic energy production. The ‚ÄúAll of the Above‚Äù approach includes fracking,  a drilling technology used for extracting oil, natural gas, geothermal energy, or water from deep underground ‚Äì accounting for two-thirds of the natural gas in the United States and halfof the nation‚Äôs oil, and positioning the U.S. as the world's leading producer of natural gas and oil. Despite the large amount of American energy it produces, fracking is under threat, as Democrats continue to attack American energy production.  A study conducted by the EPA under the Obama Administration found that fracking has had no ‚Äúwidespread, systemic impacts on drinking water resources in the United States.‚Äù  American energy production through fracking leads to lower energy prices for families and workers, boosts economic growth, and improves quality of life for Americans. The Protecting American Energy Production Act prevents a moratorium on hydraulic fracking and clarifies that states have primacy over energy production on state and private land.

More Americans are dying from fentanyl overdoses than the total number of U.S. casualties in the Vietnam War‚Äîa staggering reality that demands immediate action. This crisis is claiming over 200 lives every single day, devastating families and communities across our country.

That‚Äôs why I proudly joined a bipartisan coalition to pass the HALT Fentanyl Act, a critical measure to:

‚úÖ Permanently classify fentanyl-related substances as Schedule I drugs, closing a loophole that traffickers have exploited for too long.
‚úÖ Strengthen penalties and enforcement to dismantle trafficking networks and disrupt the flow of this lethal poison.
‚úÖ Expand research to better equip law enforcement and medical professionals in combating this epidemic.

This legislation is precise in its approach‚Äîit targets traffickers, not users. Allowing temporary scheduling to lapse would mean weaker enforcement, weaker laws, and more lives lost.

The House came together to save lives. Now the Senate must do the same.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
In Uganda, USAID helps fund the National Malaria Control Program, which sprays insecticide into village homes and distributes bed nets to pregnant women and young children.

Now, this lifesaving work is at risk.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
Trump and Elon are trying to dismantle USAID, an international relief and development agency that has saved millions of lives and helps cement America‚Äôs place as a world leader.

USAID‚Äôs work is so important ‚Äî let‚Äôs talk about what this agency actually does. üßµ

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
In Myanmar, where there were 850,000 cases of Malaria in 2023, USAID helps deliver rapid tests and drugs.

Now, these deliveries are frozen. And even if the supplies were to arrive, organizations that rely on USAID funding have no workers left to distribute the supplies.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
Across Latin America, South Asia, and Africa, dozens of clinical trials have been suspended, leaving thousands of people without researchers to supervise their care.

Trump has frozen studies on potentially life saving drugs, vaccines, and medical devices.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
In Zambia, USAID gives out rehydration salts to parents, which helps treat life-threatening diarrhea in toddlers.

Now, these treatments can‚Äôt reach villages across Zambia because the companies who transport them have had their USAID funding cut off.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
In Sudan, a country currently being torn apart by a civil war, aid has been cut off.

Their population, which is grappling with cholera, malaria, and measles, is now at higher risk of catching those diseases, spreading them, and dying from them.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
USAID helps fund health centers in the more than 25 countries where two-thirds of all child deaths occur globally.

Now, nurses have been laid off and clinics have been closed in those countries ‚Äî leaving children to die.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
USAID purchases medical equipment ‚Äî like oxygen tanks ‚Äî to support health clinics in some of the world‚Äôs poorest countries.

Now, that equipment will sit in warehouses and ports, with the staff that should be transporting them having been ordered to stop working.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
Groups that work to combat human trafficking ‚Äî from those whose efforts span the globe to those who focus on Latin America ‚Äî have had their budgets slashed.

An organization in Ecuador had to lay off 11 staff members. Others in Colombia had to shutter operations altogether.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
This freeze also hurts people in the United States.

One of USAID‚Äôs biggest missions is food aid, and about 41% of that food comes from US farmers ‚Äî worth hundreds of millions of dollars annually.

If USAID ceases these operations, that food goes to waste, & US farmers go unpaid.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
In Syria, recently devastated by an earthquake and years of war, 300 staff have been laid off and 12 field hospitals have been shuttered.

Consultations for those in need of care have been reduced from 5,000 per day to just 500 per day.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
These are the real life, human impacts. Because of this funding freeze, vulnerable individuals will be hurt. People will die. Communities will be broken.

The true scope is almost unfathomable. It is imperative that Secretary Rubio reinstate this funding immediately.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1943, Japanese forces evacuated Guadalcanal, leaving the island in Allied hands. 

Guadalcanal is the largest of the Solomons, a group of nearly 1,000 islands in the South Pacific, northeast of Australia. This American victory marked a turning point and set the stage for further Allied successes in the Solomon Islands. 

However, both sides suffered heavy losses. The U.S. lost around 1,600 men, with thousands more wounded or dying from disease. The Japanese lost 24,000 soldiers.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1962, American spy pilot Francis Gary Powers was exchanged by the Soviets for Soviet Colonel Rudolf Abel, a senior KGB agent who had been arrested in the U.S. five years earlier. 

The exchange took place on Berlin's Glienicker Bridge, with Powers and Abel crossing to freedom simultaneously.

Powers had been captured in 1960 after his U-2 reconnaissance plane was shot down by a Soviet missile while over Soviet airspace. Initially, the U.S. believed he had died, but Soviet Premier Khrushchev later revealed Powers was alive and had confessed to his mission. This exposed the U.S. cover-up, causing embarrassment for President Eisenhower just before a critical summit. Despite the scandal, Powers was later awarded the CIA‚Äôs Intelligence Star for his bravery.

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text: üßµMassachusetts‚Äô economy depends upon a vibrant Eds & Meds enterprise. The reduction of the NIH‚Äôs indirect cost recovery rate to 15% of a grant total would disrupt Massachusetts‚Äô biomedical success without increasing R&D nationally. (1/7)

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text: Research at scores of institutions like the Broad Institute, Boston Medical Center, & the University of Massachusetts launches world-changing innovation, creates good jobs, & puts Massachusetts on the map. (2/7)

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text: Overhead is well more than 15% of the cost of that research: facilities, IT, and support personnel are essential & expensive. (3/7)

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text: Some universities and hospitals may be able to cover some of their higher share of these indirect costs with cuts to other staff & programming or through more generous unrestricted philanthropy. (4/7)

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text: But the net result of a 15% indirect cap would be that NIH grants become much more expensive to accept, because of the unfunded overhead associated with them. This NIH policy is a tax on Massachusetts‚Äô Eds & Meds enterprise to the tune of ~$2 billion. (5/7)

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text: Just when diseases like Alzheimer's, heart disease, and cancer could be made treatable, America could see its young scientists discouraged, its discoveries withering on the vine, and its global leadership in science and technology receding. (6/7)

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text: Instead of this gratuitous‚Äîand almost certainly illegal‚Äîapproach, the NIH should work collaboratively on research efficiency goals and Congress must radically increase NIH funding so that the tension between direct and indirect costs is not a zero-sum equation. (7/7)

Last week, immediately upon learning of the Sunoco Pipeline leak in Upper Makefield Township, I called on the Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration (PHMSA) to immediately suspend the pipeline‚Äôs operation until a full investigation and full remediation were accomplished.  

Today, I called on Pennsylvania DEP Acting Secretary Shirley and Pennsylvania DOH Secretary Bogen for immediate answers and action regarding this ongoing pipeline leak. Jet fuel contamination has been detected in private wells, test results have been delayed, and residents are left unsure if their water is safe to drink. This situation demands full transparency, a clear remediation plan, and a thorough public investigation.

Pennsylvania's Constitution guarantees the right to clean air and pure water‚Äîa right that is now in jeopardy, and that is unacceptable.

The health and safety of our community is my top priority, and I will not stop working until every affected resident receives the answers, accountability, and action they deserve.  We must intervene at all levels of government, to include all relevant federal, state and local agencies, to make this happen.

Name: Owens, Burgess
text:
Rosa Parks, born in 1913, proved that a single decision can change the course of history. In Montgomery, Alabama in 1955, Parks quietly refused to give up her seat to a white passenger on a bus that required all Black riders to sit in the back.

Her defiance ignited the Montgomery Bus Boycott‚Äîa turning point in the Civil Rights movement that compelled a community, and eventually an entire nation, to live up to America‚Äôs values of freedom and justice for all. On Rosa Parks Day, we honor her legacy and the freedoms she helped secure for future generations.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text:
For too long, unelected bureaucrats have acted like an unaccountable fourth branch of government‚Äîshielding themselves from oversight, burying critical information, and keeping Congress in the dark about where taxpayer dollars are really going. They‚Äôve operated with impunity while hardworking Americans foot the bill.

But here‚Äôs the truth: this isn‚Äôt new. Conservatives have been sounding the alarm for years. Every time Congress rubber-stamps another bloated spending bill, these agencies get more power, more money, and less accountability. I‚Äôve voted against these reckless spending sprees and fought to slash wasteful programs ‚Äî including amendments last Congress to cut USAID funding.

Now, thanks to President Trump, @elonmusk, and @DOGE, the truth is finally coming to light. They‚Äôre exposing the corruption, the waste, and the misplaced priorities that have drained our nation. But Congress cannot sit on the sidelines and pretend we weren‚Äôt part of the problem. It‚Äôs time to take action and force real cuts. No more excuses. No more business as usual. We need to fight to rein in this out-of-control bureaucracy and put the American people back in charge.

@DOGECommittee is taking the lead on this. Tune in Wednesday.

‚ùåhire additional ICE agents
‚ùåround up and deport illegal immigrants
‚ùåfinish the wall
‚ùåcreate more detention beds

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1766, Virginia declares the Stamp Act as unconstitutional. 

In 1765, Britain was still struggling financially as a result of the French and Indian War, so to raise enough revenue, the Stamp Act was introduced. This tax required a stamp to be placed on various legal documents, newspapers, and other materials in the American colonies. It was the first direct tax levied by the British government on the colonies.

In Virginia, Patrick Henry led the Virginia Resolves, which argued that only the Virginia Assembly could impose taxes on its people. This sentiment fueled the idea of "no taxation without representation." The Virginia Resolves sparked broader colonial resistance, leading to the Stamp Act Congress in New York, where delegates outlined their objections to the British government.

In response to the protests and pressure, King George III eventually repealed the act in March 1766.

This Black History Month, we're uplifting the accomplishments and achievements of Black Americans from right here in New Jersey. 

Today, we begin with Princeton native, Paul Robeson. 

Mr. Robeson graduated as Valedictorian at Rutgers University where he was the only African-American student. 

Robeson went on to be a renaissance man. He played in the NFL, was a fixture in the Harlem Renaissance, and fought undauntedly for civil rights during the McCarthy Era. 

His childhood home still stands as a historic landmark in Mercer County. Today and every day, we remember his life and contributions.

Thurgood Marshall saw the Constitution as a living promise of equality, and he dedicated his life to making that promise a reality. After graduating from law school at Howard University, Marshall led the NAACP Legal Defense Fund, carefully planning lawsuits that culminated in Brown v. Board‚Äîa verdict that overturned the ‚Äúseparate but equal‚Äù doctrine and set the stage for the Civil Rights Movement.

After Brown v. Board, Marshall continued his legal career, eventually becoming the first Black U.S. Solicitor General in 1965 and the first Black Supreme Court Justice in 1967.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.

Since coming to Congress, I‚Äôve made it my mission to fight for transparency and safety in the food and products we rely on. The truth is both alarming and unacceptable: ingredients banned across Europe and much of the world continue to be found in countless US foods, cosmetics, and household products, silently endangering American families. These toxic substances are fueling a crisis‚Äîlinked to a surge in chronic illnesses, developmental delays, and mental health challenges sweeping our nation. 
 
I am committed to this fight, and as part of that effort, I‚Äôve launched a new initiative‚ÄîThe Wellness Watch, a series dedicated to empowering families with the knowledge they need to make safer, healthier choices. 
 
üö® This Week‚Äôs Focus: Microplastics‚ÄîMicroplastics have infiltrated our food, water, air, and our bodies. Studies link them to hormonal disruption, fertility decline, organ toxicity, immune suppression, and increased cancer risks. Laden with toxic chemicals like BPA, phthalates, and PFAS, they disrupt hormones, damage DNA, and accumulate in the body over time.

We need stronger protections and accountability. Americans deserve nothing less than transparency, accountability, and products and policies that support‚Äînot harm‚Äîour health and well-being. The clock is ticking.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Tonight, another American comes home. After more than three years of wrongful detention in a Russian penal colony, Marc Fogel‚Äîa devoted husband, father, son, and teacher from our Pennsylvania community‚Äîwill soon be back on U.S. soil, reunited with his family and free at last. His release is long overdue, but today, justice has prevailed.
 
In January, along with a bipartisan, bicameral group of my colleagues, I called on the State Department to redouble its efforts to secure Marc‚Äôs freedom, pressing for unwavering diplomatic action to bring him home. I want to thank @SecRubio, President Trump, and Special Envoy Witkoff for their leadership and shared commitment to ensuring no American is ever abandoned to injustice. Today, we celebrate Marc‚Äôs long-awaited return and reaffirm a fundamental truth: the United States stands by its citizens, and we will never stop fighting to bring every wrongfully detained American back where they belong.

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
Today, as we continue to celebrate Black History Month, I'm delighted to highlight West Chester native and renowned civil rights leader Bayard Rustin. Rustin helped organize several prominent civil rights protests, including the Freedom Rides and March on Washington, where Dr. Martin Luther King gave his "I Have a Dream speech." Unfortunately, Rustin rarely receives the recognition he deserves. 

As a gay man in the 1950s and 1960s, he was forced to work behind the scenes supporting the work of other civil rights leaders. I got to learn more about his work during a recent visit to the @ChesterCoHist Center (a plaque from the exhibit is pictured below). As President Trump continues to attack diversity, Rustin is a reminder that when it comes to civil rights and inclusion, we cannot go backward. And no matter how powerless we may feel, every day is a great day to celebrate Black excellence.
